      "author_association" : "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body" : "@esotericnonsense Binding to 0.0.0.0 means \"bind to all local addresses\" (which includes loopback, as I suspect you probably already know), and is often a default for many server daemons, so I don't see why it should be necessary to bind to loopback  specifically (unless, of course, -bind=127.0.0.1 was specified).\r\n\r\nOn a side-note:  When binding to 0.0.0.0, on some systems that support IPv6 this has the effect of also binding to ::1 in addition to 127.0.0.1 (I encountered this behaviour on Windows 7 a few years ago), but this really shouldn't be of any concern as it's a stack-implementation matter that I generally regard as being beyond the scope of most server daemons and other socket-listening applications.",
      "created_at" : "2018-02-19T20:14:15Z",
